A Capacitor app is not converted into Swift/Kotlin, but it also is not purely React running directly on the phone. It’s a hybrid architecture.

Let’s clarify exactly what happens.

What Actually Runs on the Phone

Your React app still runs as a web app, but inside a native container.

Architecture:

iOS / Android App (native container)
        │
        ▼
WebView (browser inside the app)
        │
        ▼
Your React App (HTML + JS + CSS)

So your React code runs inside a WebView, not directly on the OS.

Where Swift / Kotlin Are Used

When you run:

npx cap add ios
npx cap add android

Capacitor generates native wrapper projects.

Structure looks like:

project
│
├── src/              → React app
├── ios/              → Swift native app
└── android/          → Kotlin native app

Those native apps:

Launch a WebView

Load your React bundle

Provide native APIs through plugins

How Native Features Work

Your React code cannot directly access native APIs like:

Push notifications

Camera

Filesystem

Bluetooth

So Capacitor provides plugins.

Example:

React Code
    │
    ▼
Capacitor Bridge
    │
    ▼
Native Plugin (Swift/Kotlin)
    │
    ▼
OS Feature

Example with push notifications:

React
   │
   │ PushNotifications.register()
   ▼
Capacitor Bridge
   │
   ▼
Swift/Kotlin Plugin
   │
   ▼
APNs / Firebase SDK
In Your Case (Push Notifications)

Your code:

PushNotifications.register()

actually calls:

React JS
   │
   ▼
Capacitor Bridge
   │
   ▼
Native Push Plugin
   │
   ▼
iOS APNs / Android FCM

Then the plugin sends events back to JS.

Why the Listener Exists

When Firebase generates a token, the native plugin receives it first.

Then it emits an event to your JS code:

Native Firebase SDK
        │
        ▼
Capacitor Plugin
        │
        ▼
JS Event → FirebaseMessaging.addListener(...)

So your React code can react to it.

Important Difference

Capacitor apps are hybrid apps, not compiled native apps.

Technology	Runs JS?	Native APIs
React Web	Yes	No
Capacitor	Yes (WebView)	Yes (via plugins)
React Native	No WebView	Native components
Swift/Kotlin	No JS	Fully native

So your app is:

React + WebView + Native Plugins
Simple Mental Model

Think of Capacitor like this:

Native App Shell
      │
      ▼
Mini Browser (WebView)
      │
      ▼
Your React App

And plugins are bridges to the phone hardware.

Why This Matters For Your Push Issue

Push notifications are 100% native OS features.

So the flow is:

Firebase SDK (native)
        │
        ▼
Capacitor Plugin
        │
        ▼
JS Listener in React

Which is why you must listen for token events.
